    {
      "id": "6e7ed02fefc1d2bd9a55fec16decfc7ffd3e00fe",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2017-09-21 23:04:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3:\n\n(1 comment)\n\nIt isn't clear what the benefit of this patch is, if it is off by default, since most users will not even know it exists.  However, there probably isn't a good way to set a default value for the maximum number of rqbd buffers, since that depends greatly based on RAM and client load.\n\nI'll comment more in the Jira ticket.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "f390a6631fb5bdbfb8da58af71348419691cbe90",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2017-12-16 17:08:16.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1\n\nI think this patch is OK, but doesn’t really go far enough to solve the problem for most users. Having some default limit would be an improvement. \n\nReducing the rqbd memory usage by making a deceicated slab could be useful, if it gets us some efficiency. That is hard when the allocations are already so large. \n\nAlso, it isn’t clear why the client needs so many RPCs in flight during recovery? Having 2 per client would be enough to make good progress without overloading the server.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 3
    },
